data.content:
## What breaks: sync-over-async opt-in is removed

In the EF Core Cosmos DB provider evolution:

- **EF Core 9 (.NET 9):** Synchronous I/O on the Cosmos provider started throwing `InvalidOperationException` by default, since the underlying Cosmos SDK is async-only.
- **EF Core 10 (.NET 10):** The `EnableSyncOverAsync()` opt-in (or `ConfigureWarnings` suppression) still worked but was marked **obsolete**.
- **EF Core 11 (.NET 11):** That opt-in is **removed entirely**. All four of your methods will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime with no workaround.

## The fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`, `First()` → `FirstAsync()`, `Count()` → `CountAsync()`, `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`
- `Add()` stays synchronous (it's an in-memory tracking call, no I/O)
- This will ripple `async/await` up your call chain — callers must also become async

> **Note:** My training data has a cutoff before .NET 11 shipped. Verify the exact release notes at the [EF Core breaking changes docs](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/ef/core/what-is-new/) for the precise version where the opt-in was removed.
